{
  "mainText":"What tends to work best is true interactivity \u2014 \u201ctalking with\u201d the audience, instead of \u201ctalking to,\u201d said Mark Ghuneim, a co-founder of Trendrr, a company that tracks online chatter about television shows.\nMSNBC\u2019s \u201cDaily Rundown,\u201d for instance, has a daily trivia question, with a prize (a mention on the newscast) for the first person to submit the correct answer via Twitter.\nLast month CBS\u2019s \u201cHawaii Five-o\u201d let viewers choose the ending of an episode by commenting on Twitter and voting on CBS.com .",
  "shownText":"But sometimes bigger attempts at social TV (that\u2019s the current industry catchphrase) feel forced; for an example, look no further than the Oscars on Sunday, when the preshow was mocked for promoting an \u201cOscars mystery\u201d hashtag.\nAt other times, all the social TV talk can be downright distracting to viewers at home who don\u2019t want an overeager host to read comments from the Web and prod others to contribute.\n\nWhat tends to work best is true interactivity \u2014 \u201ctalking with\u201d the audience, instead of \u201ctalking to,\u201d said Mark Ghuneim, a co-founder of Trendrr, a company that tracks online chatter about television shows.\nMSNBC\u2019s \u201cDaily Rundown,\u201d for instance, has a daily trivia question, with a prize (a mention on the newscast) for the first person to submit the correct answer via Twitter.\nLast month CBS\u2019s \u201cHawaii Five-o\u201d let viewers choose the ending of an episode by commenting on Twitter and voting on CBS.com .\n\n\u201cOne of the things we\u2019ve learned is that the audience loves to affect the show in some meaningful way,\u201d said Fred Graver, Twitter\u2019s head of television, who praised \u201cIdol\u201d for what the series is doing with the \u201cfan meter.\u201d\n",
